	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Exercises: Linear Transformations II - Invertible Maps</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>The linear maps <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>T</latex>
                  </math> below are described in standard coordinates.</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>
					
\aligned
L\from \RNr[4] \longrightarrow \RNr[3] &amp;\quad L(x,y,z,t)= (-t+x,y+x,z-x) \\
T\from \RNr[3] \longrightarrow \RNr[4] &amp;\quad T(x,y,z) = (x+z,y,-x,-z+y)
\endaligned

				</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Answer the subsequent questions</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Show that <math>
                        <latex>(L\Comp T)</latex>
                     </math> is invertible.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We answer this problem via the following steps:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <ol>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Find the matrix <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                              </math> representing <math>
                                 <latex>L</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Find the matrix <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                              </math> representing <math>
                                 <latex>T</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>The matrix representing <math>
                                 <latex>(L\Comp T)</latex>
                              </math> is then the matrix product <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{C}:=\Mtrx{A}\cdot \Mtrx{B}</latex>
                              </math>
                           </para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
						               <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>We then know that <math>
                                 <latex>(L\Comp T)</latex>
                              </math> is invertible exactly when <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                              </math> is invertible. So, we may test <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                              </math> for invertibility by checking if its determinant is nonzero.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </li>
					             </ol>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <strong>Step 1</strong>   The matrix <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> representing <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> has the following vectors as its columns:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>L(\StdBss{1})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(1,1,-1)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>L(\StdBss{2})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(0,1,0)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>L(\StdBss{3})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(0,0,1)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>L(\StdBss{4})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(-1,0,0)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore,</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A}\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] 
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <strong>Step 2</strong>   Similarly, the matrix <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> representing <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> has the following vectors as its columns:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>T(\StdBss{1})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(1,0,-1,0)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>T(\StdBss{2})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(0,1,0,1)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>T(\StdBss{3})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(1,0,0,-1)</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore,</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{B}\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <strong>Step 3</strong>   The matrix representing <math>
                           <latex>(L\Comp T)</latex>
                        </math> is</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\Mtrx{C} := 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 1 \\
1 &amp;  1 &amp; 0 \\
-2 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <strong>Step 4</strong> testing <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                        </math> for invertibility. We find that <math>
                           <latex>\det(\Mtrx{C})=2</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore, <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{B})</latex>
                        </math> is invertible, and so  <math>
                           <latex>(L\Comp T)</latex>
                        </math> is invertible.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find <math>
                        <latex>(L\Comp T)^{-1}(x,y,z)</latex>
                     </math> for an arbitrary vector <math>
                        <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>(L\Comp T)^{-1}(x,y,z) = (-(1/2)z , y + (1/2)z , x+y+z)</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Using the first part of the problem, we see</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
(\Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{B})^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 1 \\
1 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
-2 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 
\end{array}
\right]^{-1} = 
\dfrac{1}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\
2 &amp; 2 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Accordingly, we obtain</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
(L\Comp T)^{-1} (x,y,z)\ =\ 
\dfrac{1}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\
2 &amp; 2 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right] 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x \\ y \\ z
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
-\tfrac{1}{2}z \\ y + \tfrac{1}{2} z \\ x + y + z
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Determine if <math>
                        <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                     </math> is invertible. Explain your answer.</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                           </math> is not invertible.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix representing <math>
                           <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                        </math> is <math>
                           <latex>(B\cdot A)</latex>
                        </math>, and</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\det(\Mtrx{B} \Mtrx{A})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore <math>
                           <latex>(\Mtrx{B} \Mtrx{A})</latex>
                        </math> is not invertible and, consequently, <math>
                           <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                        </math> is not invertible.</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Note that this result may be explained conceptually as follows: in the composite <math>
                           <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                        </math>, we first execute the linear map <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math>. Now <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> transforms <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                        </math> into the lower dimensional <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math>. In the process some ‘collapsing’ of material in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                        </math> must occur; for example the nullspace of the matrix <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> gets collapsed into the 0-vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math>. Once such collapsing has occurred, it can never be reversed by another linear map. So <math>
                           <latex>(T\Comp L)</latex>
                        </math> is not invertible.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Let <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\Vect{b}_2,\Vect{b}_3)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\EuScript{D}=(\Vect{d}_1,\Vect{d}_2,\Vect{d}_3)</latex>
                  </math> be the ordered bases of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> with</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>
					
\aligned
\Vect{b}_1 &amp;= (1,0,0), &amp;\quad \Vect{b}_2 &amp;= (-1,-1,1), &amp;\quad \Vect{b}_3 &amp;= (0,0,1) \\
\Vect{d}_1 &amp;= (1,0,1), &amp;\quad \Vect{d}_2 &amp;= (-1,-1,0), &amp;\quad \Vect{d}_3 &amp;= (0,-1,-1)
\endaligned

				</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Further, let <math>
                     <latex>L\from \RNr[3] \to \RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> be the linear map which is represented by the matrix</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{D}} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; -2 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]

				</latex>
			         </math.display>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{D}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math> representing <math>
                        <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
                     </math> with respect to the bases <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math> for the domain and <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{D}</latex>
                     </math> for the target.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{D}\EuScript{B}} = \left( \Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{D}}\right)^{-1} =
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; -2 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]^{-1} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{D}</latex>
                     </math>-coordinates of <math>
                        <latex>L^{-1}(a,b,c)_{\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math>, where <math>
                        <latex>(a,b,c)_{\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math> is arbitrary in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}}=(a,b,c)</latex>
                        </math>, then</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
L^{-1}(\Vect{x})_{\EuScript{D}} = \Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{D}\EuScript{B}} \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} = \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
a \\ b \\ c
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
c \\ -b \\ a-2b
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Find the matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> representing <math>
                        <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
                     </math> with respect to the standard basis of  <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.display>
						                  <latex>
							
\Mtrx{A} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
-1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

						</latex>
					                </math.display>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}=\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{S}}</latex>
                        </math> representing <math>
                           <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
                        </math> with respect to the standard basis of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                        </math> is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\aligned
\Mtrx{A}\ &amp;=\ \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{S}\EuScript{D}}\cdot \Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{D}\EuScript{B}}(L^{-1})\cdot \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{S}} \\
	&amp;=\ 
	\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]^{-1} \\
	&amp;=\ 
	\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
-1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \\
-1 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]
\endaligned

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>If <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{S}}=(x,y,z)</latex>
                     </math>, express <math>
                        <latex>L^{-1}(\Vect{x})</latex>
                     </math> in standard coordinates.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <math.array column="3">
                        <row rowspan="1">
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>L^{-1}(x,y,z)</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                           <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                              <math>
                                 <latex>(z,-x-2y,-x+z)</latex>
                              </math>
                           </cell>
                        </row>
                     </math.array>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Suppose <math>
                     <latex>L\from \RNr[n] \to \RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> is a linear map such that, whenever <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{u}_1,\dots ,\Vect{u}_r</latex>
                  </math> are linearly independent vectors in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>, the vectors <math>
                     <latex>L(\Vect{u}_1),\dots ,L(\Vect{u}_r)</latex>
                  </math> are also linearly independent.  Show that <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> is invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>The hypothesis applies, in particular to a basis of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>Choose an ordered basis <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}=(\Vect{b}_1,\dots ,\Vect{b}_n)</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>. The vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math> are linearly independent. So <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{D}:=(L(\Vect{b}_1),\dots ,L(\Vect{b}_n))</latex>
                     </math> is linearly independent and, hence, an ordered basis of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}_{\EuScript{D}\EuScript{B}}</latex>
                     </math> representing <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> with respect to these two bases is the identity <math>
                        <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                     </math>-matrix. This matrix is invertible, and so <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> is invertible. – This was to be shown.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
