			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Suppose there is a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>V</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>L(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                     </math>, and suppose <math>
                        <latex>M=L^{-1}</latex>
                     </math>. Then <math>
                        <latex>M</latex>
                     </math> reverses the transformation effect of <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math>. What does this mean in the case at hand?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Previous hint continued: in the case at hand, this means</para.body>
               </para>
					          <ol>
						            <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{0} = M\Comp L(\Vect{0}) = M(\Vect{0})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
						            <li>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x} = M\Comp L(\Vect{x}) = M(\Vect{0})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </li>
					          </ol>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>So ... ?</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Let us analyze the situation: suppose there is a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math> with <math>
                           <latex>L(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math>, and suppose <math>
                           <latex>M=L^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>. Then <math>
                           <latex>M</latex>
                        </math> reverses the transformation effect of <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore,</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>M\Comp L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=	</latex>
                           </math>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the assumption <math>
                                          <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the assumption <math>
                                          <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>M(\Vect{0})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>=	</latex>
                           </math>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the general fact: every linear function <math>
                                          <latex>M</latex>
                                       </math> satisfies <math>
                                          <latex>M(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                           <companion>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Here we use the general fact: every linear function <math>
                                          <latex>M</latex>
                                       </math> satisfies <math>
                                          <latex>M(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This means that for an isomorphism <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> there is never an <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}\neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math> with <math>
                           <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
